Sure! To include the `.env` file in your `.gitignore`, simply add it to the list. Here's the updated `.gitignore` file for a Node.js project with `.env` included:

```plaintext
# Node.js
node_modules/
npm-debug.log*
yarn-debug.log*
yarn-error.log*

# Logs
logs
*.log
logs/*.log

# Directory for instrumented libs generated by jscoverage/JSCover
lib-cov

# Coverage directory used by tools like istanbul
coverage/

# Grunt intermediate storage (https://gruntjs.com/creating-plugins#storing-task-files)
.grunt/

# Bower dependency directory (https://bower.io/)
bower_components/

# Dependency directories
jspm_packages/

# TypeScript cache
*.tsbuildinfo

# Optional npm cache directory
.npm

# Optional eslint cache
.eslintcache

# Optional REPL history
.node_repl_history

# Output of 'npm pack'
*.tgz

# dotenv environment variable files
.env
.env.test
.env.production

# Next.js build output
.next/

# Nuxt.js build output
.nuxt/

# Vuepress build output
.vuepress/dist

# Serverless directories
.serverless/

# FuseBox cache
.fusebox/

# DynamoDB Local files
.dynamodb/

# TernJS port file
.tern-port

# Stylint configuration
.stylintcache

# IntelliJ IDEA files
.idea/

# Visual Studio Code files
.vscode/

# Sublime Text files
*.sublime-project
*.sublime-workspace

# MacOS files
.DS_Store

# Windows thumbnail cache files
Thumbs.db

# Folder config file
desktop.ini

# VS Code Extension settings
.vscode/

# Temporary files created by IDEs or text editors
*.swp
*~
.*.swp
.*.swo

# Project build artifacts and config files
dist/
build/
tmp/
temp/
out/
bin/
obj/

# Log files
*.log

# SASS cache
.sass-cache/

# Next.js build output
.next/

# Nuxt.js build output
.nuxt/

# Vuepress build output
.vuepress/dist

# Serverless directories
.serverless/

# FuseBox cache
.fusebox/

# dotenv environment variable files
.env
```